I89. Special postage stamps

I11(a) In order to afford the public a convenient way to contribute to funding for breast cancer research, the Postal Service shall establish a special rate of postage for first-class mail under this section.

I11(b) The rate of postage established under this section_

I12(1) shall be equal to the regular first-class rate of postage, plus a differential of not less than 15 percent;

I12(2) shall be set by the Governors in accordance with such procedures as the Governors shall by regulation prescribe (in lieu of the procedures under chapter 36); and

I12(3) shall be offered as an alternative to the regular first-class rate of postage.

Q04

I10The use of the special rate of postage established under this section shall be voluntary on the part of postal patrons. The special rate of postage of an individual stamp under this section shall be an amount that is evenly divisible by 5.

I11(c)(1) Of the amounts becoming available for breast cancer research pursuant to this section, the Postal Service shall pay_

I12(A) 70 percent to the National Institutes of Health; and

I12(B) the remainder to the Department of Defense.

Q04

I10Payments under this paragraph to an agency shall be made under such arrangements as the Postal Service shall by mutual agreement with such agency establish in order to carry out the purposes of this section, except that, under those arrangements, payments to such agency shall be made at least twice a year.

I11(2) For purposes of this section, the term ``amounts becoming available for breast cancer research pursuant to this section'' means_

I12(A) the total amounts received by the Postal Service that it would not have received but for the enactment of this section, reduced by

I12(B) an amount sufficient to cover reasonable costs incurred by the Postal Service in carrying out this section, including those attributable to the printing, sale, and distribution of stamps under this section,

Q04

I10as determined by the Postal Service under regulations that it shall prescribe.

I11(d) It is the sense of the Congress that nothing in this section should_

I12(1) directly or indirectly cause a net decrease in total funds received by the National Institutes of Health, the Department of Defense, or any other agency of the Government (or any component or program thereof) below the level that would otherwise have been received but for the enactment of this section; or

I12(2) affect regular first-class rates of postage or any other regular rates of postage.

